{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569701"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:31:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:31:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22284"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22284"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.07,0.06,0.47,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111391"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15249"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22284"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93522"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43769"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111391"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with a three-day history of fever, right flank pain, and dysuria. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. Her regular medications include metformin, perindopril, and amlodipine. She works as a personal trainer and takes creatine supplements to enhance her muscle performance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. She has marked right costovertebral angle tenderness. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 125 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 15.2 \u00d7 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 12.8 \u00d7 10^9/L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 130 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 45 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine microscopy: \u0026gt;100 white blood cells/high power field, numerous bacteria\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is most likely to make the estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) misleading in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypertension","Type 2 diabetes","Female sex","Acute kidney injury","Urinary tract infection"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with acute pyelonephritis (fever, flank pain, dysuria, leukocytosis, and pyuria) and has an elevated creatinine with reduced eGFR, suggesting acute kidney injury (AKI) secondary to the infection. The eGFR calculation is based on serum creatinine and assumes a steady state of creatinine production and clearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute kidney injury\u003C/strong\u003E makes eGFR calculations misleading because there is a rapid change in kidney function without the steady state that eGFR equations assume. In AKI, serum creatinine is rising (or falling during recovery), and has not reached equilibrium. The eGFR equations were developed and validated in patients with stable kidney function. Therefore, in this patient with likely AKI from pyelonephritis, the reported eGFR may be an inaccurate reflection of her true kidney function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E alone does not significantly affect the reliability of eGFR calculations. While hypertension is a risk factor for chronic kidney disease, it does not directly interfere with the relationship between serum creatinine and GFR in a way that would make eGFR calculations systematically inaccurate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E, like hypertension, is a risk factor for kidney disease but does not inherently make eGFR calculations unreliable. The presence of diabetes does not alter the relationship between serum creatinine and actual GFR in a way that would systematically bias eGFR calculations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemale sex\u003C/strong\u003E is actually accounted for in most eGFR calculation formulas (such as the CKD-EPI and MDRD equations), which include sex-specific factors to adjust for the generally lower muscle mass and creatinine production in women compared to men. Therefore, female sex does not make eGFR unreliable when using appropriate equations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E itself does not directly affect the reliability of eGFR calculations. However, if the infection leads to AKI (as is likely in this case), then it is the AKI, not the infection per se, that makes the eGFR misleading. It would be a factor that would make albumin measurement unreliable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that this patient\u0027s use of creatine supplements could also affect the reliability of eGFR calculations by increasing serum creatinine levels independent of kidney function. Additionally, her occupation as a personal trainer suggests she may have higher muscle mass than average, which could also lead to higher creatinine production and potentially lower eGFR estimates than her true kidney function would indicate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) is misleading in acute kidney injury as it assumes a steady state of creatinine production and clearance.","Patients with severe liver disease have reduced creatinine production, making eGFR calculations inaccurate.","Dietary factors such as high protein intake or creatine supplements can artificially alter serum creatinine levels without reflecting true kidney function."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93522"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22284"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93522"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T19:29:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T19:29:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15249"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111391"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"